Transfer the rice to a serving platter and garnish with the remaining green onions. Serve hot.

recipes.name: ROASTED CABBAGE STEAKS
recipes.description: Add volume to your plate with this easy-to-make, nutrient-packed side that's super low in calories, fat, and carbs. Roasting the cabbage mellows the flavor, while garlic adds a kick. Cabbage is high in vitamins C and K, contains anti-aging compounds, and is high in fiber to help keep you full.
instructions: Preheat the oven to 350°F (177°C). Line a 9 x 13in (23 x 33cm) baking sheet with aluminum foil and lightly spray with non-stick cooking spray.

Slice the cabbage crosswise into ½-inch-thick (1.25cm) steaks. Place the steaks on the baking sheet and lightly spray with non-stick cooking spray. Evenly spread the garlic over the steaks, and season with the salt and black pepper.
Bake for 35 to 45 minutes, or until the steaks become soft and translucent and begin to brown around the edges. Serve hot.
tips: Store in an airtight container in the refrigerator for up to 3 days. These can be reheated, or eaten cold. (When eaten cold, they have a taste and texture similar to sauerkraut.)
For a more umami flavor, omit the salt and spray liquid aminos evenly over the cabbage steaks. (Approximately 6 sprays has 0 calories, and adds a soy sauce-like flavor.)
Amp up the heat by adding ¼ tsp red pepper flakes.
recipes.nutrition_full: 88 CALORIES | 2.2 GRAMS PROTEIN | 8.2 GRAMS CARBOHYDRATES | 0.4 GRAMS FAT

recipes.name: CLOUD BREAD
recipes.description: When the carb cravings strike, strike back with this light and airy bread alternative that will satisfy those nagging cravings! The key is to whip the egg whites to a light peak, then gently fold in the egg yolks for a chewiness and crust that could easily be mistaken for the real thing!
ingredients: 4 large eggs, warmed to room temperature
4 tbsp light cream cheese, softened and warmed to room temperature
instructions: Preheat the oven to 350°F (177°C). Line two 9 x 13in (23 x 33cm) baking sheets with parchment paper.
Separate the egg yolks from the egg whites, placing the yolks in a medium bowl and the whites in a large glass or metal mixing bowl. (Do not use a plastic bowl for the egg whites.)
Add the cream of tartar to the egg whites. Using a hand mixer, beat the egg whites on high speed until they form stiff peaks that don't collapse when the mixer blade is lifted from the bowl.
Add the salt and cream cheese to the egg yolks, and whisk until all ingredients are well incorporated. Use a rubber spatula to gently fold the egg yolk mixture into the egg whites.
Use a 1/4 cup measuring cup to measure the batter into individual mounds on the baking sheet, maintaining at least 1 inch (2.5cm) between each mound.
Bake for 20 to 25 minutes, rotating the baking sheets halfway through the baking process to ensure the bread bakes evenly. Allow the bread to cool on the baking sheets.
tips: Insert sheets of parchment paper between each piece and store in an airtight container in the refrigerator for up to 7 days.
For a richer flavor, season the unbaked batter mounds with 1/2 tsp dried rosemary, 1/2 tsp garlic powder, and 1 tsp parmesan cheese. This will add only a few calories per serving.

recipes.name: HERB-ROASTED VEGETABLES
recipes.description: This dish is ideal for weekly meal prep. It's simple to make, and the leftovers taste even better the next day! The roasting process brings out the natural sweetness of the squash and carrots, while mellowing and caramelizing the onion. Zucchini and squash are both high in fiber and vitamins.
ingredients: 2 large zucchini squash, sliced crosswise into 1/2-inch (1.25cm) slices
2 large yellow squash, sliced crosswise into 1/2-inch (1.25cm) slices
1 medium red onion, sliced into 1-inch (2.5cm) wedges
instructions: Preheat the oven to 400°F (204°C). Line a large baking sheet with parchment paper.
In a large bowl, combine the zucchini, squash, carrots, and onion wedges. Lightly spray the vegetables with non-stick cooking spray.
Make the seasoning by combining the garlic powder, thyme, parsley, rosemary, and salt in a small bowl. Mix well. Sprinkle the seasoning mix over the vegetables and toss thoroughly to coat.
Spread the vegetables in an even layer on the baking sheet. Roast for 15 minutes.
Using tongs, flip the vegetables and roast for an additional 15 minutes, or until the vegetables are soft and slightly caramelized. Serve hot.
recipes.nutrition_full: 45 CALORIES | 1.8 GRAMS PROTEIN | 9.4 GRAMS CARBOHYDRATES | 0.2 GRAMS FAT

recipes.name: ROSEMARY BEEFSTEAK TOMATOES
recipes.description: Fragrant rosemary livens up this simple dish, and contrasts beautifully with hearty beefsteak tomatoes. Allowing the tomatoes to soak up the seasonings will make them tender and enhance their sweetness. This simple side is a snap to prepare, and is ready to serve in under 30 minutes.
ingredients: 4 medium beefsteak tomatoes, sliced into quarters, skin and seeds left intact
instructions: In a small bowl, combine the rosemary, garlic powder, paprika, and salt. Mix well.
In a large bowl, combine the tomatoes and seasonings. Gently toss to thoroughly coat the tomatoes with the seasonings.
Allow the tomatoes to rest for 15 to 20 minutes to absorb the seasonings before serving. Serve at room temperature.
tips: This dish is best made and served immediately, as the tomatoes can become mealy when stored in the refrigerator.
For a different herbal twist, substitute 1 tsp chopped fresh basil for the rosemary.
recipes.nutrition_full: 26 CALORIES | 1 GRAM PROTEIN | 5.7 GRAMS CARBOHYDRATES | 0.1 GRAMS FAT

recipes.name: CITRUS KALE SALAD
recipes.description: Vibrant pops of color invite you to dig into this nutrient-dense salad. Oranges add just a touch of sweetness, perfectly complementing the slightly bitter kale, which is packed with antioxidants, vitamins, and fiber. Poppy seeds add a nutty element, which pairs well with the onion.
ingredients: 2 cups kale, washed, ribs removed, and chopped into 1⁄2-inch (1.25cm) strips
1⁄2 naval orange, peeled, separated into wedges, and cut into thirds
instructions: In a large bowl, combine the kale strips, orange segments, and onion slices. Set aside.
In a medium bowl, combine the canola oil, stevia, lime juice, vinegar, salt, and poppy seeds. Whisk to combine.
Pour the dressing over the salad and gently toss to coat. Serve immediately.
tips: You can buy pre-sliced onions and bagged kale for easier meal prep.
This recipe is best prepared and served fresh. The dressing can be made ahead of time and stored in an airtight container in the refrigerator for up to one week.
recipes.nutrition_full: 43 CALORIES | 1.6 GRAMS PROTEIN | 5.5 GRAMS CARBOHYDRATES | 1.4 GRAMS FAT

recipes.name: WILTED SPINACH AND CHERRY TOMATO SALAD
recipes.description: This simple, nutrient-dense salad features deep, vibrant greens, pops of plump red cherry tomatoes, and a light and refreshing dressing. Spinach is packed with potassium, fiber, and contains anti-inflammatory properties to help your body recover from tough workouts.
instructions: Spray a large skillet with non-stick cooking spray and place over medium heat. Add the garlic and cook for 2 to 3 minutes, or until it begins to soften and becomes fragrant.
Add the spinach to the skillet in small handfuls, tossing repeatedly for 2 to 3 minutes to ensure that the leaves are evenly cooked. Transfer the cooked spinach to a serving bowl.
Add the tomatoes, lemon juice, salt, and black pepper to the spinach. Gently toss to thoroughly coat the spinach in the dressing. Serve warm.
tips: This salad is best when prepared and served fresh, as it can become mushy in the refrigerator.
recipes.nutrition_full: 28 CALORIES | 2.5 GRAMS PROTEIN | 2.5 GRAMS CARBOHYDRATES | 0.8 GRAMS FAT

recipes.name: FRESH VEGGIE STIR FRY
recipes.description: Eastern flavors and loads of fresh vegetables transform this simple stir fry into a satisfying, low calorie side. The broccoli becomes sweet and fork tender, while bok choy adds balance, and the cabbage adds fiber to keep you full. Fresh ginger brightens the flavors and aids with digestion.
ingredients: 1 cup broccoli florets, fresh or frozen
instructions: Spray a large frying pan with non-stick cooking spray and place over medium-high heat. Add the ginger and garlic to the pan and cook for 1 to 2 minutes, or until the garlic softens and becomes fragrant.
Add the bok choy, broccoli, cabbage, and soy sauce. Cook for 2 to 3 minutes, stirring frequently.
Add the sliced mushrooms and cook for an additional 2 minutes, stirring frequently.
Add the chicken broth, cover, and reduce the heat to low. Steam for 4 to 5 minutes, or until the broccoli is tender and can be pierced with a knife. Serve hot.
tips: If using frozen broccoli florets, make sure to thaw them in the refrigerator 1 day before using.
Store in an airtight container in the refrigerator for up to 6 days.

recipes.name: GUACAMOLE DEVILED EGGS
recipes.description: This twist on deviled eggs offers heart-healthy fats, and palate-awakening flavors. Lime juice adds a surprising kick, while paprika brings color and a hint of heat. Healthy fats aid in satiety, while the egg whites provide protein and a vessel for the yolky-guacamole goodness.
instructions: Separate the egg yolks from the egg white halves. Place the yolks in a large bowl, and place the whites in a separate, medium bowl.
Slice the avocado in half, remove the seed, and scoop the flesh into the bowl containing the yolks. Add the lime juice, cilantro, onion flakes, garlic powder, salt, and black pepper.
Use a fork or potato masher to thoroughly mash the ingredients together until a smooth consistency is achieved and no lumps remain.
Arrange the egg white halves on a serving platter, sliced sides up, and spoon equal amounts of the filling into each egg white half. Sprinkle the paprika over top of the eggs. Serve chilled.

recipes.name: ROASTED BRUSSELS SPROUTS AND FENNEL
recipes.description: Brussels sprouts and fennel aren't at the top of everyone's list of favorite sides, but this dish will change that! Both are low in fat, and packed with beneficial nutrients and antioxidants. Roasting caramelizes the exteriors, while keeping the insides delicate and sweet.
ingredients: 16oz (450g) Brussels sprouts, ends trimmed and halved lengthwise
2 fennel bulbs, cores removed and thinly sliced
instructions: Preheat the oven to 400°F (204°C). Line a large baking sheet with aluminum foil.
In a large bowl, combine the Brussels sprouts and fennel slices, and lightly spray with non-stick cooking spray.
Add the garlic, salt, and black pepper, and gently toss to coat the vegetables with the seasonings.
Spread the vegetables in a single layer on the baking sheet. Roast for 25 to 30 minutes, tossing every 10 minutes to ensure the vegetables are evenly cooked. Serve hot.
tips: Store in an airtight container in the refrigerator for up to 5 days.
recipes.nutrition_full: 46 CALORIES | 3.0 GRAMS PROTEIN | 9.7 GRAMS CARBOHYDRATES | 0.8 GRAMS FAT

recipes.name: LEMONY GRILLED ASPARAGUS
recipes.description: Mild, earthy asparagus is jazzed up with fresh lemon, while onion and garlic add savory sharpness, and fresh lemon zest adds vibrant contrast to this dish. Asparagus is high in fiber, nutrients, and detoxifying compounds. This is a simple side that keeps well and can be made ahead for meal prep.
ingredients: 1 bunch young asparagus (approximately 20 spears), woody ends trimmed
instructions: In a large bowl, combine the asparagus spears and lemon juice. Toss to coat, and allow to rest at room temperature for 30 minutes.

Preheat a grill to medium. Transfer the asparagus to a plate and pat dry with a paper towel. Spray the spears with non-stick cooking spray and season with the onion powder, garlic powder, salt, and black pepper.
Grill the spears for 2 to 3 minutes per side, or until they form a nice char and have good caramelization. Transfer to a serving platter and garnish with the lemon zest. Serve hot.
tips: You can double or triple this recipe for easy meal prep.
Store in an airtight container in the refrigerator for up to 5 days.
recipes.nutrition_full: 42 CALORIES | 3.7 GRAMS PROTEIN | 9.3 GRAMS CARBOHYDRATES | 0.3 GRAMS FAT

recipes.name: SNAPPY GINGER GREEN BEANS
recipes.description: This recipe satisfies the need to snack on something crunchy, without derailing your meal plan. Blanching the beans prevents them from becoming dull and rubbery. Instead, they're crisp and refreshing, and when paired with the seasonings they're a tasty, healthy alternative to chips.
ingredients: 2 cups fresh green beans, rinsed and ends trimmed
instructions: In a large pot, bring the chicken broth to a low boil over medium heat.
Add the green beans to the pot and blanche for 5 to 7 minutes. With a slotted spoon, immediately transfer the beans to a large bowl filled with ice water. Set aside to cool.
In a small bowl, make the ginger sauce by combining the ginger root, sesame seeds, salt, lemon juice, and garlic. Mix well.
Drain the ice water from the green beans. Pour the ginger sauce over the green beans, and toss gently to coat. Serve immediately.
tips: Always use fresh green beans for this recipe. Frozen or canned beans won't have the same snap or flavor.
Store in an airtight container in the refrigerator for up to 2 days.

recipes.name: CRUNCHY AVOCADO SALAD
recipes.description: Creamy avocado and sweet cherry tomatoes come together in this refreshing, antioxidant-rich salad that features a satisfying crunch and just a hint of heat. The avocado and olive oil provide healthy monounsaturated fats, which can help reduce inflammation and aid recovery.
ingredients: 2 large ripe avocados, halved lengthwise, seed removed, and cut into ½-inch (1.25cm) cubes
1 cup cherry tomatoes, sliced into halves
1 seedless cucumber, cut into ½-inch (1.25cm) cubes
½ medium red onion, finely diced
⅓ cup finely chopped fresh cilantro
instructions: In a large bowl, combine the avocado, tomatoes, cucumber, onion, and cilantro. Mix well.
Sprinkle the lemon juice over top and season with the salt. Add the olive oil, and gently toss with a rubber spatula until all ingredients are well combined. Serve immediately.
tips: Store in an airtight container in the refrigerator for up to 3 days.
If you're not a fan of cilantro, you can use 2 tbsp finely chopped parsley, instead.
recipes.nutrition_full: 163 CALORIES | 2.0 GRAMS PROTEIN | 9.3 GRAMS CARBOHYDRATES | 16.9 GRAMS FAT

recipes.name: PUMPKIN AND OAT BARS
recipes.description: Pricey store-bought bars often contain loads of sugar and preservatives. These spiced bars are healthier, and are great as a snack or for a post-workout refuel. Pumpkin keeps the bars moist, and oat flour adds whole grain nutrition and fiber. This bar does some heavy lifting!
ingredients: 1 cup canned pumpkin purée (not pumpkin pie mix)
instructions: Preheat the oven to 350°F (177°C). Spray an 8 x 8in (20 x 20cm) baking pan with non-stick cooking spray.
In a large bowl, combine the oat flour, protein powder, baking powder, salt, cinnamon, allspice, ginger, and stevia. Mix well.
In a separate large bowl, combine the egg whites, pumpkin purée, and vanilla extract. Mix well.
Make the batter by adding the wet ingredients to the dry ingredients. Mix well to combine.
Pour the batter into the baking pan. Bake for 20 to 25 minutes, or until a toothpick inserted in the middle comes out clean. Slice into 6 equal-sized bars.
tips: If you don't have oat flour, you can make your own by milling dry oats in a blender until they reach a flour-like consistency.
Individually wrap the bars in plastic wrap and store in an airtight container in the refrigerator for up to one week.
Try substituting mashed sweet potato or squash for the pumpkin.

recipes.name: QUICK AND EASY EGG BITES
recipes.description: These bite-sized bundles of protein are a snap to make, and can be modified to fit your tastes and meal plan. You can experiment with a variety of vegetables and spices, they're easier to make and more portable than an omelet, and they store well in the refrigerator.
instructions: Preheat the oven to 350°F (177°C). Spray a large muffin tin with non-stick cooking spray.
In a large bowl, combine the egg whites, tomato, onion, salt, and black pepper. Mix well.
Pour equal amounts of the egg white mixture into six muffin cups. Bake for 18 to 20 minutes, or until the centers are set and firm. Serve warm.
tips: Double this recipe and keep the muffins on hand as a quick snack.
Store in an airtight container in the refrigerator for up to one week.

Make these bites keto by replacing the egg whites with 6 large eggs, and adding 1/4 cup shredded sharp cheddar cheese. The macros will be 223 calories, 15.7g fat, 2.6g carbs, and 16.8g protein per serving.
Make post-workout muffins by omitting the salt, pepper, tomatoes, and onions, and adding stevia, vanilla, cinnamon, and berries.
recipes.nutrition_full: 136 CALORIES | 28.6g PROTEIN | 3.7g CARBOHYDRATES | 0.1g FAT

recipes.name: GRILLED BALSAMIC MELON AND CHEESE
recipes.description: This simple yet refreshing muscle-building snack creates a delightful flavor and textural contrast when the cottage cheese is paired with the grilled melon. Watermelon is refreshing, hydrating, and also high in lycopene, which is a key antioxidant compound.
ingredients: 4 slices watermelon, rind on, sliced into 1-inch-thick (2.5cm) triangles
instructions: Preheat a grill to high. Lightly spray each watermelon slice with coconut oil cooking spray, and evenly drizzle the balsamic vinegar over each watermelon slice.
Grill the watermelon slices for 1 to 2 minutes per side, or until they are lightly seared and develop grill marks on each side.
Transfer the watermelon slices to a plate. Lightly season the slices with the salt, and top with the basil. Add the cottage cheese to the plate. Serve chilled.
tips: This recipe is best when prepared and served fresh.
For meal prep, you can grill the watermelon ahead of time and store it lightly sealed in plastic wrap in the refrigerator. Add the cottage cheese and basil just before serving.
recipes.nutrition_full: 260 CALORIES | 30g PROTEIN | 28g CARBOHYDRATES | 3.7g FAT

recipes.name: GREEK YOGURT HUMMUS
recipes.description: Silky smooth with a punch of lemon, this hummus is a light and balanced snack. Greek yogurt adds tartness, and also increases the serving size without drastically increasing the calories. Chickpeas are high in fiber and vitamins, and also a good source of vegetarian protein.
ingredients: 1 small carrot, peeled and sliced lengthwise into sticks
instructions: In a blender or food processor, combine the chickpeas, Greek yogurt, lemon juice, garlic powder, cumin, paprika, and salt. Pulse at 15 second intervals until the ingredients are well incorporated and no lumps remain.

Scrape the sides of the blender with a rubber spatula and blend on high for an additional 60 seconds, or until a smooth and creamy consistency is achieved. (If the hummus is too thick, add additional water, 1 tbsp at a time, until the desired consistency is reached.)
Transfer to a serving bowl. Serve chilled with the carrot sticks and cucumber slices on the side.
recipes.nutrition_full: 152 CALORIES | 8.5 GRAMS PROTEIN | 26.2 GRAMS CARBOHYDRATES | 2.0 GRAMS FAT

recipes.name: NO-BAKE COCOA AND OATS BARS
recipes.description: This bar tastes like a dessert, but still fits the macros for most bodybuilding meal plans. The unsweetened cocoa powder offers a potent antioxidant and energy boost, and the oats and oat bran add complex carbs for energy. Pop one of these into your bag for a quick snack between meals!
ingredients: 1/3 cup vanilla protein powder (whey and casein blend)
instructions: Spray a small, sealable food storage container (approximately 8 x 8in (20 x 20cm)) with non-stick cooking spray.

In a medium bowl, combine the oats, oat bran, almond flour, cocoa powder, stevia, and protein powder. Mix well to combine. In a separate medium bowl, combine the almond milk and vanilla extract. Mix well to combine.
Make the batter by adding the dry ingredients to the wet ingredients. Mix the ingredients until a thick, uniform consistency is achieved.
Spoon the batter into the prepared container, and use a spoon to smooth and flatten the mixture. Refrigerate for 15 minutes before slicing into 3 bars.
almond milk and thicken the batter.
Individually wrap the bars in plastic wrap and store in an airtight container in the refrigerator for up to one week.
tips: For a more intense chocolate flavor, substitute ¼ cup chocolate whey protein powder for the vanilla whey protein powder.

recipes.name: PALEO PROTEIN CRACKERS
recipes.description: Everyone craves crunchy snacks, but all too often they're off limits on most bodybuilding meal plans. These crackers will fit into most meal plans, and will also satisfy those cravings for some crunch. Flax and sesame seeds provide healthy fats and create a texture that's perfect for dipping!
instructions: Preheat the oven to 350°F (177°C). Line a large baking sheet with parchment paper.
In a large bowl, combine the egg whites, almond flour, flax meal, sesame seeds, parsley, tarragon, chives, thyme, and sea salt.

Using clean hands, mix the ingredients until a dough is formed, then shape the dough into a ball. (If the dough is too crumbly, add more egg whites, one tablespoon at a time, until the desired consistency is reached.)

Place the dough on the baking sheet. Place another sheet of parchment paper over top of the dough, and use a rolling pin to roll the dough out as thin as possible. Score the dough into 24 even-sized squares.
Bake for 20 to 25 minutes, or until the crackers turn golden brown. Allow to cool, and break the crackers into even-sized pieces.

recipes.name: CHOCOLATE PROTEIN SNACK MUG
recipes.description: Kick those nagging sweet tooth cravings to the curb and get a shot of protein with this personal-sized mug cake that is full of chocolatey goodness. Cocoa powder satisfies the palate and provide a little kick of caffeine, while protein powder and egg whites feed the muscles.
instructions: In a microwave-safe, medium-sized mug, combine the cocoa powder, coconut flour, protein powder, and baking powder. Stir well.
Add the egg whites and almond milk. Mix all ingredients well.

Microwave on high for 1 to 2 minutes, checking every 15 seconds for doneness. The cake is done when the center is set and no longer appears shiny. (Make sure not to overcook the cake, as it can quickly become rubbery and dry.) Serve warm.
tips: Make the mix ahead of time by combining the cocoa powder, coconut flour, protein powder, and baking powder, and storing the mix in individual portions in zipper lock bags. When you're ready for a snack, just pour the ingredients in a mug, and add the egg whites and almond milk.
recipes.nutrition_full: 190 CALORIES | 2.1g TOTAL FAT | 9.2g TOTAL CARBS | 34.3g PROTEIN

recipes.name: ZESTY TUNA SNACK BOWL
recipes.description: Canned tuna is an inexpensive source of protein and a great way to maximize your training budget. This low fat take on traditional tuna salad features naturally sweet vegetables, garlicky pickles, and tangy condiments that will all help keep the macros on track. You won't miss the mayo!
ingredients: 1 5oz (140g) can light tuna packed in water, rinsed and drained
instructions: In a small glass bowl, combine the tuna, celery, carrot, pickle, lemon juice, mustard, and Greek yogurt.
Stir well to incorporate all ingredients. Serve chilled.
tips: Store in an airtight container in the refrigerator for up to 5 days.
For a non-dairy option, omit the Greek yogurt. This will eliminate 27 calories, 2.1g carbs, and 4.5g protein.
Make it keto by adding half a medium avocado to the bowl. Total macros per serving will be 324 calories, 13.8g fat, 12.1g carbs, and 38g protein.
recipes.nutrition_full: 194 CALORIES | 37.3 GRAMS PROTEIN | 7.1 GRAMS CARBOHYDRATES | 1.8 GRAMS FAT

recipes.name: TURKEY AND VEGGIE ROLL-UP
recipes.description: Stave off cravings with this salty and crunchy snack that's low in fat, and ready in less than 10 minutes. Lean turkey keeps you full and delivers muscle-building protein, while juicy tomato, crunchy spinach, and crisp cucumber all come together to create a light and delicate roll.
instructions: Using a vegetable peeler, slice the cucumber lengthwise into long, thin strips. Arrange the cucumber strips in a row on a sheet of plastic wrap, overlapping them slightly to form a square. Place the turkey slices on top of the cucumber strips.
Spread the mustard in a thin layer over the turkey. Add the spinach in a thin layer, then spoon the chopped tomato in a narrow column near one edge of the wrap.
Create the roll-up by grasping the plastic wrap at the end with the tomatoes, and rolling the ingredients into a tight roll. (Make sure not to roll the plastic wrap into the roll-up.)
Discard the plastic wrap. Secure the ingredients by inserting a toothpick at each end, and carefully transferring the roll-up to a plate. Serve immediately.
tips: This recipe is best prepared and served immediately, as the cucumber can become soggy quickly.
recipes.nutrition_full: 160 CALORIES | 26.3g PROTEIN | 11.4g CARBOHYDRATES | 1.4g FAT

recipes.name: CARROT CAKE SHAKE
recipes.description: Greek yogurt and banana make up the creamy base of this shake. Cardamom's citrus scent intensifies the carrot flavor, while ginger adds a sweet heat.
instructions: Place the carrots in a microwave-safe dish, cover with a damp paper towel, and microwave on high for 1 minute. Allow to cool for 5 minutes.
Combine all ingredients in a blender. Blend on high for one minute. Scrape the sides of the blender with a rubber spatula, and blend on high for 1 additional minute.
recipes.nutrition_full: 290 CALORIES | 33.4g PROTEIN | 37.2g CARBOHYDRATES | 1.7g FAT

recipes.name: ELVIS SHAKE
recipes.description: Channel "The King" with this recipe, except here Elvis has a six pack and trains six days a week. Powdered peanut butter and banana will rock your taste buds, without racking up the calories.
ingredients: ¼ cup vanilla whey protein powder
instructions: Combine the banana, powdered peanut butter, almond milk, protein powder, vanilla, stevia, and ice in a blender. Blend on low for 30 seconds.

Scrape the sides of the blender with a rubber spatula. Blend on high for an additional 30 seconds to 1 minute, or until the ice is crushed and the shake is smooth and creamy. Transfer to a glass and serve immediately.
tips: For a thicker shake, omit the ice and use a frozen banana (make sure to peel and slice the banana before freezing).

recipes.name: GOLDEN MILK SHAKE
recipes.description: Golden milk is touted for its anti-inflammatory, digestive, and recovery benefits. MCTs (medium-chain triglycerides) from the coconut oil provide energy.
instructions: Combine the coconut milk, protein powder, cottage cheese, coconut oil, ginger, turmeric, cinnamon, black pepper, stevia, and ice in a blender. Blend on low for 30 seconds, or until the ingredients are well incorporated.
Scrape the sides of the blender with a rubber spatula. Blend on high for one additional minute, or until the shake is smooth and creamy. Transfer to a glass and serve immediately.
recipes.nutrition_full: 294 CALORIES | 34g PROTEIN | 11g CARBOHYDRATES | 13.8g FAT

recipes.name: KEY LIME SHAKE
recipes.description: Tart lime, coconut, and vanilla flavors give this shake a delectable tropical flavor. You'll reap the nutritional benefits of a full serving of spinach, but you won't taste it at all!
instructions: Combine the Greek yogurt, protein powder, lime juice, coconut milk, stevia, spinach, and ice in a blender. Blend on low for 1 minute.
Scrape the sides of the blender with a rubber spatula. Blend on high for an additional 30 seconds to 1 minute, or until the shake is smooth and creamy. Transfer to a glass and serve immediately.
recipes.nutrition_full: 222 CALORIES | 31.9g PROTEIN | 14.1g CARBOHYDRATES | 4.6g FAT

recipes.name: BLUEBERRY CHEESECAKE SHAKE
recipes.description: Juicy blueberries combine with tart Greek yogurt to create a shake that tastes like a decadent dessert. The Greek yogurt, protein powder, and almond milk all power the protein up to over 30g per serving. This shake is delicious when made with virtually any type of sweet berry.
ingredients: 1/2 cup fat free plain Greek yogurt
instructions: Combine the blueberries, protein powder, Greek yogurt, vanilla extract, almond milk, and ice in a blender. Pulse for 15 second intervals until the ingredients are well incorporated.

Scrape the sides of the blender with a rubber spatula. Blend on high for 1 additional minute, or until the ice is crushed and the shake is smooth and creamy. Transfer to a glass and serve immediately.
tips: Buy frozen fruit in bulk and store it in your freezer. Frozen fruit is often just as delicious as fresh, and is usually less expensive. Most fresh fruit also freezes well.
recipes.nutrition_full: 266 CALORIES | 32.5g PROTEIN | 32g CARBOHYDRATES | 1.3g FAT

recipes.name: ORANGE CREAMSICLE SHAKE
recipes.description: This tart and sweet shake is elevated by juicy orange and a touch of orange zest, while Greek yogurt adds protein and creates an ice cream-like consistency.
ingredients: 1 orange, peeled and cut into segments, seeds and pith removed
instructions: Combine the orange zest, orange segments, protein powder, Greek yogurt, almond milk, vanilla extract, stevia, and ice in a blender. Blend on low for 30 seconds.
Scrape the sides of the blender with a rubber spatula. Blend on high for an additional 1 to 2 minutes, or until the shake is smooth and creamy. Transfer to a glass and serve immediately.
recipes.nutrition_full: 247 CALORIES | 32.7 GRAMS PROTEIN | 26.9 GRAMS CARBOHYDRATES | 1.3 GRAMS FAT

recipes.name: COCO-CHOCO ALMOND SHAKE
recipes.description: This shake is more satisfying than a candy bar! Healthy fats from the almond butter and coconut keep the carbs low, and antioxidant-rich cocoa powder provides an extra boost of energy.
instructions: Combine the almond milk, protein powder, almond butter, cocoa powder, coconut, and stevia in a blender. Blend on high for 30 seconds.
Scrape the sides of the blender with a rubber spatula, and blend on high for 1 additional minute.
Transfer to a glass and top with the slivered almonds. Serve immediately.
recipes.nutrition_full: 328 CALORIES | 30.6g PROTEIN | 9.5g CARBS | 20.9g FAT

recipes.name: HULK SHAKE
recipes.description: Smash cravings with this green powerhouse! Fiber from the spinach will keep you feeling full, and a touch of tart lemon juice adds balance to the sweet banana.
instructions: Add the almond milk, spinach, lemon juice, and banana to a blender. Blend on high for 1 minute.

Scrape the sides of the blender with a rubber spatula. Add the protein powder, stevia, and cinnamon. Blend for 1 minute, or until the shake is smooth and creamy. Transfer to a glass and serve immediately.
tips: This shake can be made ahead and refrigerated for up to 2 days.

recipes.name: Chocolate Avocado Mousse
instructions: Add all ingredients to a food processor or high-speed blender.
Blend until smooth and creamy, scraping down sides as needed.
Add almond milk if mixture is too thick.
Taste and adjust sweetness if desired.
Divide between 2 bowls and chill for at least 30 minutes before serving.
Serve chilled with fresh berries or chopped nuts if desired.
recipes.tips: For a spicier twist, add 1/4 tsp ground chipotle powder.

recipes.name: Custard Recipe Variations
tips: For a chocolatey twist, add 1 tbsp unsweetened cocoa powder and 1 tsp powdered stevia to the custard mix. This will add only 5 calories to each serving.
For an added indulgence, top the cooked custards with 1 tbsp finely chopped almonds. This will add 50 calories, 5g fat, 2g carbs, and 3g protein per serving.

recipes.name: GAINS GLAZED DONUTS
recipes.description: You'll make sweet gains with these low-carb, protein-glazed donuts! Coconut flour gives them a cake-like texture, and the proteins will all be digested at different speeds, so you can enjoy these as a snack or even after a workout. These are perfect for a sweet protein boost.
ingredients: 1 cup vanilla protein powder (whey and casein blend)
instructions: Preheat the oven to 350°F (177°C). Spray a donut pan with non-stick cooking spray.

In a large bowl, combine the protein powder, coconut flour, baking powder, cinnamon, stevia, and salt. Mix well. In a separate medium bowl, combine the coconut oil, egg whites, vanilla extract, and almond milk. Mix well.

Make the batter by adding the wet ingredients to the dry ingredients. Mix until all ingredients form a smooth, pourable batter. (If the batter is too thick, add more almond milk, 1 tbsp at a time, until the desired consistency is achieved.)

Pour the batter into four donut cups. Bake for 9 to 12 minutes. The donuts are done when a toothpick inserted in the middle comes out clean. Remove the donuts from the pan and place on a cooling rack. Repeat the steps with the remaining batter.
Make the glaze by combining the almond milk and protein powder in a small bowl. Mix thoroughly, and allow to thicken for 5 minutes.
Drizzle the glaze over the cooled donuts. Serve warm.
tips: Store in an airtight container at room temperature for up to 6 days.
